I. Multiple linear regression: Simulated data

Problem 1

Run the following code to create the vectors x1, x2, and y.

set.seed(1)
n <- 100
x1 <- runif(n)
x2 <- runif(n,10,20)
y <- 2+2*x1+0.3*x2+rnorm(n)

a. (1 pts) The last line of the code above corresponds to creating a linear model in which y is a function of x1 and x2. Write out the form of the linear model. What are the values of the regression coefficients \(\beta_0\), \(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_2\)? What is the value of \(\sigma^2\)?

The linear model is \(Y=2+2X_1+0.3X_2+\epsilon\) which is lm(y ~ x1 + x2) in R.

\(\beta_0=2\), \(\beta_1=2\), and \(\beta_2=0.3\). \(\sigma^2=1\).

b. (1 pts) Use the function cor() to calculate the correlation coefficient between x1 and x2. Create a scatter plot using ggplot2 displaying the relationship between the variables x1 and x2. What can you say about the direction and strength of their relationship?

correlation = cor(x1, x2)
correlation
## [1] 0.01703215

The correlation coefficient between x1 and x2 is 0.0170321.

x1x2 = data.frame(x1, x2)
ggplot(data = x1x2, mapping = aes(x = x1, y = x2))+
  geom_point()+
  ggtitle("Scatterplot of x1 and x2") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

According to our correlation coefficient 0.0170321 and the scatterplot, it may have not strong, positive, linear relationship.

c.(2 pts) Fit a least squares regression to predict y using x1 and x2. Describe the obtained results. What are the values of \(\hat{\beta_0}\), \(\hat{\beta_1}\) and \(\hat{\beta_2}\)? How do these relate to the true values of \(\beta_0\), \(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_2\)? What is the value of s and how does it relate to the true value of \(\sigma^2\)? Can you reject the null hypothesis \(H_0:~\beta_1=0\)? How about the null hypothesis \(H_0:~\beta_2=0\)?

model = lm(y ~ x1 + x2)
model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x1 + x2)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)           x1           x2  
##      1.9763       1.9307       0.3014

From the above code we can know that \(\hat{\beta_0}\) = 1.9762757, \(\hat{\beta_1}\) = 1.9307364, and \(\hat{\beta_2}\) = 0.3014356. They are estimators of \(\beta_0\), \(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_2\).

Since \(\beta_0=2\), \(\beta_1=2\), and \(\beta_2=0.3\), which are similar to \(\hat{\beta_0}\) = 1.9762757, \(\hat{\beta_1}\) = 1.9307364, and \(\hat{\beta_2}\) = 0.3014356. We may say that they are relative good estimators.

s = sum((model$residuals)^2)/(n-2-1)
s
## [1] 0.9360869

From the code above, we can see that \(s\) = 0.9360869. Since \(\sigma^2\) = 1, which is similar to 0.9360869. So s is a relative good estimator of \(\sigma^2\).

In exercise 1, we got the same result when doing linear regressions lm(y ~ x1 + x2), lm(y ~ x1), and lm(y ~ x2), which is rejecting the null hypotheses: \(\beta_1 = 0\) or \(\beta_2=0\), which means that \(\beta_1\) or \(\beta_2\) may not be 0.

However, in exercise 2, when doing linear regression lm(y ~ x1 + x2), we fail to reject the null hypotheses, which means \(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_2\) can be 0.

When we do linear regression lm(y ~ x1), we reject the null hypothesis, which means that \(\beta_1\) may not be 0.

When we do linear regression lm(y ~ x2), we reject the null hypothesis, which means that \(\beta_2\) may not be 0.

The results are not consistent in exercise 2.

This difference is mainly because of the two datasets have different distributions of data. In exercise 1, the correlation coefficient is about 0.01703215. However, in exercise 2, the correlation coefficient is about 0.9975904.

model = lm(y ~ x1 + x2)
vif(model)
##       x1       x2 
## 207.7504 207.7504

We can see from above the collinearity is 207.7504, which is very large. When x1 and x2 are highly correlated, it may have collinearity. In this case, it is difficult to determine x1 and x2 separately with y correctly because collinearity affects the accuracy of \(\hat{\beta_1}\) and \(\hat{\beta_2}\).

II. Multiple Linear Regression: Application

Load the Carseats data set contained in the ISLR library. Carseats is a simulated data set containing sales of child car seats at 400 different stores.

It contains the following variables:

  • Sales: Unit sales (in thousands) at each location

  • CompPrice: Price charged by competitor at each location

  • Income: Community income level (in thousands of dollars)

  • Advertising: Local advertising budget for company at each location (in thousands of dollars)

  • Population: Population size in region (in thousands)

  • Price: Price company charges for car seats at each site

  • ShelveLoc: A factor with levels Bad, Good and Medium indicating the quality of the shelving location for the car seats at each site

  • Age: Average age of the local population

  • Education: Education level at each location

  • Urban: A factor with levels No and Yes to indicate whether the store is in an urban or rural location

  • US: A factor with levels No and Yes to indicate whether the store is in the US or not

For this Problem you will consider only Sales, Price, Income, Urban, ShelveLoc and Advertising.

Problem a

(2 points) Graphically explore the relationship between the six above variables (use the ggpairs function in the GGally). Comment on the plots: are they bivariate or univariate plots? Describe the plots (x-axis, y-axis, etc). What do you notice in the distribution of the variable advertising?

From the Ljung Box test and Durbin-Watson test, since the p-values are very large, we fail to reject the null hypothesis (the residuals are independent). As a result, we may conclude that the residuals are not correlated.

From the plot of the residuals, we can see that the residuals does not have heteroskedasticity.

Problem g

(2 points) Consider the variable Advertising. Create a variable called Advertising_levels which is equal to None if Advertising=0, Low if Advertising is less than 10, Medium if Advertising is between 10 and 20, and High otherwise. Fit the reduced model in (e) including the variable Advertising_levels instead of the variable Advertsing. Interpret the coefficients of the variable Advertising_levels and compare it with the coefficient of Advertising given by the model in (e).

df = as.data.frame(Carseats)
df$Advertising_levels[df$Advertising==0] = "None"
df$Advertising_levels[df$Advertising<=10&df$Advertising!=0] = "Low"

When the Advertising levels (Low) increase by 1 unit, the sales will decrease 2.2599509 on average, given other variables are fixed.

When the Advertising levels (Medium) increase by 1 unit, the sales will decrease 1.6462465 on average, given other variables are fixed.

When the Advertising levels (None) increase by 1 unit, the sales will decrease 3.0328953 on average, given other variables are fixed.

In problem e, when the Advertising increase by 1 unit, the sales will increase 0.10562 on average, given other variables are fixed.

The coefficient of Advertising we got in problem e is 0.10562. However, the coefficients we got in this problem, we got Advertising levels (Low) coefficient is -2.2599509, Advertising levels (Medium) coefficient is -1.6462465, Advertising levels (None) coefficient is -3.0328953.

It is possible that when the advertising level is high, sales will increase.
